         <abstract>
            <p>The author's thesis is that international political and economic developments provide the key to the determination of future long-term investment policy. He forecasts that international fiscal and monetary constraints, an increasing domestic labor force and increasingly competitive world markets will dampen domestic inflationary pressures over the next five years. Based upon the foregoing analysis, the author argues that opportunities for successful equity investment in the United States stock markets will become increasingly selective, with international issues favored. Municipal bonds and tax sheltered real estate investments are viewed as holding portfolio attraction under the hypothesized conditions of relative price stability combined with rising corporate and individual tax rates.</p>
          </abstract>
